Dala Hill situated in Dala local government area of Kano Metropolis, Nigeria, represents a crucial natural and cultural heritage site. Its historical significance dates back to the establishment of the Kano Kingdom, believed to have originated around Dala Hill [32], [33]. The hill, standing at 534 meters with a circumference of 788 meters, was a primary source of iron ore, attracting skilled artisans in the seventh century [34]. Mythologically, it was the dwelling place of the deity Tsumburbura and her high priest Barbushe, who protected the inhabitants [2], [32], [35], [36]. Moreover, its geographical location is $12^{\circ} 00^{\prime} 33^{\prime \prime}
N ,
8^{\circ} 30^{\prime} 32^{\prime\prime}$E in Dala Local Government bordered by several other settlements including Yalwa, Madigawa, Gwammaja, Dogon Nama, Kantudu, Bakin Ruwa, Adakawa, and Kabuwaya [19].
